<subSubSection pageId="124" pageNumber="125" type="diversity">
<paragraph pageId="124" pageNumber="125">Diversity.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="124" pageNumber="125">
Worldwide, with about 135 species arrayed in three genera: 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Kirby" authorityYear="1830" class="Hexapoda" family="Rhysodidae" genus="Clinidium" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="124" pageNumber="125" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="124" pageNumber="125">Clinidium</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(about 75 species), 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bell &amp; Bell" authorityYear="1978" class="Hexapoda" family="Rhysodidae" genus="Grouvellina" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="124" pageNumber="125" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="124" pageNumber="125">Grouvellina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Bell and Bell (17 Madagascan species), and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Fairmaire" authorityYear="1895" class="Hexapoda" family="Rhysodidae" genus="Rhyzodiastes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="124" pageNumber="125" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="124" pageNumber="125">Rhyzodiastes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Fairmaire (about 45 species). The vast majority of species are found in the Southern Hemisphere, with only 11 species (about 8% of the world fauna) occurring in the Northern Hemisphere.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
